# Research report: What is the efficacy and safety of tirzepatide for glycemic control and weight loss in adults with type 2 diabetes?

### Efficacy

In the same trial, tirzepatide also induced significantly greater weight loss, with reductions of −7.8 kg, −10.3 kg, and −12.4 kg for the 5 mg, 10 mg, and 15 mg doses, respectively, compared to −6.2 kg with semaglutide 1 mg.[1] Weight loss in SURPASS-3 was also substantial, with changes of −7.5 kg, −10.7 kg, and −12.9 kg for the three tirzepatide doses, respectively, versus a weight gain of 2.3 kg with insulin degludec.[1] A pre-planned exploratory analysis of SURPASS-2 and SURPASS-3 found that the median time to achieve an HbA1c <7.0% was faster with tirzepatide (8.1 weeks across doses) than with semaglutide 1 mg (12.0 weeks) or insulin degludec (12.1 weeks).[2] At the same 104-week timepoint in SURPASS-4, body weight reductions were −7.6 kg, −10.0 kg, and −11.4 kg for the tirzepatide doses, versus a gain of 2.1 kg with insulin glargine.[3] In the SURPASS-AP-Combo trial in an Asia-Pacific population, all tirzepatide doses were superior to insulin glargine for HbA1c reduction at 40 weeks, with least squares mean reductions of −2.24%, −2.44%, and −2.49% for the 5 mg, 10 mg, and 15 mg doses, respectively, versus −0.95% with insulin glargine.[4] The same trial reported superior body weight reductions with tirzepatide: −5.0 kg, −7.0 kg, and −7.2 kg for the three doses, respectively, compared to a gain of 1.5 kg with insulin glargine.[4] A post-hoc subgroup analysis of SURPASS-AP-Combo found that reductions in HbA1c and body weight with tirzepatide were generally consistent across subgroups defined by age, sex, baseline BMI, and diabetes duration.[5] The corresponding weight reductions in SURPASS J-mono were −5.8 kg, −8.5 kg, and −10.7 kg for tirzepatide versus −0.5 kg with dulaglutide.[1]

### Safety

Gastrointestinal adverse events are the most common tolerability concern with tirzepatide and are typically mild to moderate in severity.[6] A systematic review and meta-analysis of randomized clinical trials reported that gastrointestinal adverse events were the most frequently reported category in tirzepatide-related individual case safety reports in a real-world pharmacovigilance database, with pancreatitis and vomiting being the most common specific events.[7] For vomiting, incidence with tirzepatide 15 mg ranged from 6% to 18.1%, and for diarrhea, it ranged from 12% to 31%.[1] One systematic review found that compared to 5 mg, tirzepatide 10 mg and 15 mg were associated with more frequent nausea, and 15 mg led to more diarrhea than 5 mg, suggesting some dose-dependence for specific gastrointestinal events.[8] The risk of hypoglycemia with tirzepatide is generally low when not used with insulin or insulin secretagogues.[9] Regarding thyroid safety, real-world pharmacovigilance data has detected a disproportionate reporting signal for medullary thyroid cancer with tirzepatide (ROR 13.67, 95% CI 4.35–42.96).[10] This aligns with a boxed warning for thyroid C-cell tumors seen in rodents, and it is unknown whether tirzepatide causes such tumors in humans, including medullary thyroid carcinoma.[11] However, the same real-world analysis noted tirzepatide exhibited a similar risk of medullary thyroid cancer compared to GLP-1 receptor agonists.[10] Furthermore, a review noted that pivotal trials in the SURPASS program did not report clinically meaningful increases in autoimmune thyroid disease or sustained thyroid dysfunction.[12] Discontinuation due to adverse events appears dose-related; one systematic review found the risk of discontinuation by adverse event was significantly higher with tirzepatide 10 mg (pooled RR=1.75, 95%CI[1.16-2.63]) and 15 mg (pooled RR=2.03, 95%CI [1.37-3.01]) compared to GLP-1 receptor agonists.[8]

### Comparative

An adjusted indirect treatment comparison (aITC) suggests tirzepatide 10 and 15 mg also provide superior glycemic and weight control compared to the higher semaglutide 2 mg dose approved for diabetes, with estimated differences in HbA1c of −0.36% and −0.4% and in body weight of −3.15 kg and −5.15 kg, respectively.[13] A systematic review and network meta-analysis of RCTs concluded that all tirzepatide doses were comparable to semaglutide 2.0 mg and superior to semaglutide 1.0 mg and 0.5 mg in reducing HbA1c, while tirzepatide 15 mg, 10 mg, and 5 mg demonstrated greater weight loss efficacy than semaglutide 2.0 mg, 1.0 mg, and 0.5 mg, respectively.[14] A post-hoc analysis of SURPASS-2 found tirzepatide was superior to semaglutide 1 mg in achieving composite therapeutic targets; for example, 57% of participants on tirzepatide 15 mg met three or more standard targets (HbA1c <7%, systolic BP <130 mmHg, LDL-cholesterol <100 mg/dL, and weight loss >10%) compared to 34% on semaglutide.[15] Compared to basal insulin, a meta-analysis of SURPASS trials showed tirzepatide provides superior HbA1c reduction (mean differences ranging from −0.89% to −1.23% across doses) and profound weight loss benefits (mean differences from −8.41 kg to −12.49 kg) versus weight gain with insulin.[16] In a network meta-analysis of patients with type 2 diabetes on basal insulin, tirzepatide 5, 10, and 15 mg showed statistically significant, greater reductions in HbA1c and body weight versus the GLP-1 RA dulaglutide 1.5 mg.[17] Regarding cardiovascular outcomes, the SURPASS-CVOT trial found tirzepatide was noninferior to dulaglutide for major adverse cardiovascular events (MACE), with a hazard ratio of 0.92 (95.3% CI, 0.83 to 1.01).[18] A real-world trial emulation study reported a hazard ratio of 1.06 (95% CI, 0.95 to 1.18) for MACE including mortality in a head-to-head comparison of tirzepatide versus semaglutide, suggesting comparable cardiovascular benefit.[19] The aforementioned aITC reported the overall safety profile was similar between tirzepatide and semaglutide 2 mg.[13]

### Dose Response

This dose-response relationship for HbA1c reduction was consistent across trials; in SURPASS-4 at 104 weeks, mean reductions were -2.3%, -2.5%, and -2.6% for the 5 mg, 10 mg, and 15 mg doses, respectively.[3] Weight loss also followed a clear dose-dependent pattern, with greater reductions at higher doses.[20] In SURPASS-2, body weight reductions were -7.8 kg, -10.3 kg, and -12.4 kg for tirzepatide 5 mg, 10 mg, and 15 mg, respectively, a trend replicated in SURPASS-4 with reductions of -7.6 kg, -10.0 kg, and -11.4 kg at 104 weeks.[21][3] A meta-analysis confirmed that compared to the 5 mg dose, the 10 mg and 15 mg doses provided significantly greater weight loss of -2.64 kg and -4.26 kg, respectively.[22] The proportion of patients achieving weight loss thresholds also increased with dose; in SURPASS-2, 65%, 76%, and 80% of patients achieved ≥5% weight loss on 5 mg, 10 mg, and 15 mg, respectively, while ≥15% weight loss was achieved by 15%, 24%, and 36%.[1] An adjusted indirect treatment comparison estimated that tirzepatide 10 mg and 15 mg provided significantly greater HbA1c and body weight reductions compared to semaglutide 2 mg, while the 5 mg dose showed similar efficacy to semaglutide 2 mg.[13] The time to achieve glycemic and weight loss targets was faster with all tirzepatide doses compared to active controls, with the median time to reach HbA1c <7.0% being 8.1 weeks for each tirzepatide dose versus 12.0 weeks for semaglutide 1 mg.[2] Regarding safety, gastrointestinal adverse events were common and showed a dose-dependent increase in incidence.[20] A meta-analysis reported that the risk of total adverse events was significantly higher with the 10 mg and 15 mg doses compared to the 5 mg dose.[22] One meta-analysis concluded that within the 5–15 mg range, glycemic and weight efficacy is dose-dependent, with the 15 mg dose providing the greatest efficacy benefit, while the 5 mg dose may offer a more favorable safety profile.[20]

### Population Subgroups

A post-hoc subgroup analysis of SURPASS-AP-Combo found that the efficacy of tirzepatide was generally consistent across subgroups defined by age, sex, baseline HbA1c, BMI, body weight, and diabetes duration, though some differences were observed.[5] Patients with higher baseline body weight (≥75 kg) experienced significantly greater weight loss across all tirzepatide doses compared to those weighing <75 kg.[5] A post-hoc analysis of pooled SURPASS-1 to -5 data reported that tirzepatide's effect on HbA1c reduction was consistent between participants aged <65 and ≥65 years.[23] In a small observational pilot study of older Japanese patients (mean age 79.5 years), tirzepatide initiation improved time in range from 53.2% to 78.9% as measured by continuous glucose monitoring.[24] For patients with high cardiovascular risk, the SURPASS-4 trial specifically enrolled individuals with type 2 diabetes and increased cardiovascular risk, demonstrating superior HbA1c and weight reductions with tirzepatide versus insulin glargine.[25] The subsequent SURPASS-CVOT trial, which enrolled patients with type 2 diabetes and established atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease, found tirzepatide was non-inferior to dulaglutide for the primary composite cardiovascular endpoint (hazard ratio 0.92; 95% CI 0.83 to 1.01).[18] A real-world trial emulation analysis benchmarking against SURPASS-CVOT estimated a hazard ratio of 0.87 (95% CI 0.75 to 1.01) for a composite outcome including mortality for tirzepatide versus dulaglutide in an expanded population.[19] The safety profile, characterized predominantly by gastrointestinal adverse events, was generally consistent across these populations and trials.[4][26][5][18]

### Limitations

Limitations: The corpus is dominated by lower-tier sources, with only 18% of sources classified as T1 primary studies. High-severity contradictions were detected on the effect of tirzepatide on body weight and weight loss, with sources disagreeing on the magnitude of the effect by several hundred to several thousand percent. The evidence horizon spans from 2010 to the present, but the low proportion of high-tier evidence limits the strength of conclusions.

## Methods
Pre-registered protocol.json (SHA-256 e69a2c914405fdc1...).
Corpus: Serper + Semantic Scholar + OpenAlex live retrieval, augmented by domain backends (clinical: scope_query_validator: 8 kept / 23 dropped).
Generator model: deepseek/deepseek-v3.2-exp (multi-section: outline + 5 parallel sections + strict_verify + regen-on-failure).
Evaluator model: qwen/qwen3-8b (different family).
Sources classified using T1-T7 tier taxonomy.
Inclusion / exclusion per clinical template. Sponsor / conflict-of-interest review per source.
Prompt-injection sanitization enabled. Retrieved 2026-04-20.
Expected tier distribution: T1 30-60%, T2 15-40%, T3 5-25%, T4 0-20%, T5 0-15%, T6 0-10%, T7 0-10%. Actual distribution: T1=18%, T2=14%, T3=1%, T4=39%, T5=2%, T6=2%, T7=23%, UNKNOWN=1%.
Corpus adequacy: decision=proceed, 7/7 thresholds met.
Completeness checklist: 7/7 topics covered.

## Contradiction disclosures
The contradiction detector flagged 13 numeric disagreements across the evidence pool. Most are extraction artifacts produced by grouping different endpoints (e.g. HbA1c % vs body-weight %), different doses, different populations (T2D vs obesity-without-diabetes), or different comparators under the same subject/predicate label. The detector does NOT adjudicate by endpoint, population, dose, timepoint, or source tier; raw detector output is available in `contradictions.json`. Per-flag enumeration (PT08 disclosure):

- tirzepatide / body weight (10 mg): cited values range 5.0 to 93.5 % (source tiers: T1, T2).
- tirzepatide / body weight (15 mg): cited values range 6.5 to 48.4 % (source tiers: T7, T1).
- tirzepatide / body weight (5 mg): cited values range -1.75 to 95.0 % (source tiers: T4, T2).
- tirzepatide / weight loss: cited values range 1.8 to 57.0 % (source tiers: T2, T4, T7, T5).
- tirzepatide / weight loss (0.5 mg): cited values range 2.46 to 15.0 % (source tiers: T1, T4).
- tirzepatide / weight loss (1 mg): cited values range 13.2 to 95.0 % (source tiers: T4, T2).
- tirzepatide / weight loss (10 mg): cited values range -83.0 to 26.4 % (source tiers: T4, T1, T2).
